WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.587 --> 00:00:02.282
<v ->Alan Wallace was raised a Christian</v>

2
00:00:02.282 --> 00:00:04.085
in Pasadena, California,

3
00:00:04.085 --> 00:00:06.239
but something in him simply couldn't find

4
00:00:06.239 --> 00:00:08.085
a comfortable place in his world.

5
00:00:08.085 --> 00:00:10.890
As a young adult, he headed for India, not surprisingly,

6
00:00:10.890 --> 00:00:13.396
learned to speak Tibetan with ease,

7
00:00:13.396 --> 00:00:15.487
and became a student of the Dalai Lama,

8
00:00:15.487 --> 00:00:18.313
a relationship that has lasted 37 years.

9
00:00:18.313 --> 00:00:21.310
During his years of deep seclusion and meditation,

10
00:00:21.310 --> 00:00:24.852
Alan began writing on the essential truths about happiness,

11
00:00:24.852 --> 00:00:27.433
including the Buddhist belief that we are not

12
00:00:27.433 --> 00:00:29.592
entitled to happiness.

13
00:00:37.714 --> 00:00:39.901
You've spent many, many years of your life

14
00:00:39.901 --> 00:00:42.258
living in the Buddhist tradition.

15
00:00:42.258 --> 00:00:45.111
How did this originally happen for you?

16
00:00:47.442 --> 00:00:49.618
<v ->As I was growing up,</v>

17
00:00:49.618 --> 00:00:52.795
I was, on the one hand raised in a very religious household.

18
00:00:52.795 --> 00:00:55.046
My father's a theologian,

19
00:00:55.046 --> 00:00:58.278
and a lot of religion on both sides of my family tree.

20
00:00:58.278 --> 00:01:00.101
On the one hand.

21
00:01:00.101 --> 00:01:01.733
On the other hand, from a very early age,

22
00:01:01.733 --> 00:01:03.696
age of 13, I was very strongly drawn

23
00:01:03.696 --> 00:01:05.264
to a career in science.

24
00:01:05.264 --> 00:01:06.906
Specifically in biology.

25
00:01:06.906 --> 00:01:10.341
And so as I was growing up, I just felt increasingly

26
00:01:10.341 --> 00:01:13.071
that the whole world view presented by modern science,

27
00:01:13.071 --> 00:01:15.791
especially with its materialistic underpinnings,

28
00:01:15.791 --> 00:01:18.756
was really fundamentally incompatible

29
00:01:18.756 --> 00:01:21.337
with the world view presented every Sunday.

30
00:01:21.337 --> 00:01:22.777
<v Interviewer>In church.</v>

31
00:01:22.777 --> 00:01:24.244
<v ->In church, exactly, yeah.</v>

32
00:01:24.244 --> 00:01:27.839
And I just didn't find anybody at all, frankly,

33
00:01:27.839 --> 00:01:31.604
who could unite these two worlds into one coherent whole,

34
00:01:31.604 --> 00:01:34.441
where the parts really fit in a meaningful

35
00:01:34.441 --> 00:01:36.170
and harmonious fashion.

36
00:01:36.170 --> 00:01:39.358
So by the time I was 20, I'd really pretty well given up.

37
00:01:39.358 --> 00:01:41.619
I figured, "This society's not working for me,"

38
00:01:41.619 --> 00:01:43.464
because I couldn't, like many people can,

39
00:01:43.464 --> 00:01:46.568
I couldn't simply throw out religion lock, stock and barrel,

40
00:01:46.568 --> 00:01:47.955
like, "What a bunch of hooey.

41
00:01:47.955 --> 00:01:50.632
"What a bunch of nonsense and superstition."

42
00:01:50.632 --> 00:01:54.333
I think that is a rather primitive response

43
00:01:54.333 --> 00:01:57.810
to many of the most brilliant minds we've had

44
00:01:57.810 --> 00:02:00.636
in the whole world, not only Western civilization,

45
00:02:00.636 --> 00:02:02.769
have been profoundly religious.

46
00:02:02.769 --> 00:02:04.007
<v Interviewer>But a common response</v>

47
00:02:04.007 --> 00:02:05.042
for people who are frustrated.

48
00:02:05.042 --> 00:02:06.301
<v ->Oh, it's very common.</v>

49
00:02:06.301 --> 00:02:09.169
It's very common, but I think it's rather facile.

50
00:02:09.169 --> 00:02:11.057
I think it's rather facile.

51
00:02:11.057 --> 00:02:14.545
And that is these were not ninnies, you know?

52
00:02:14.545 --> 00:02:16.806
And to brush them off as if we in the 21st century

53
00:02:16.806 --> 00:02:19.419
somehow have such greater insight

54
00:02:19.419 --> 00:02:22.854
strikes me as just being

55
00:02:22.854 --> 00:02:24.731
not very self-critical.

56
00:02:24.731 --> 00:02:25.883
<v Interviewer>But do you think that perhaps</v>

57
00:02:25.883 --> 00:02:28.604
some of the later interpretations and translations

58
00:02:28.604 --> 00:02:30.438
could have been done by ninnies? (laughs)

59
00:02:30.438 --> 00:02:31.558
<v ->Oh, that's for sure,</v>

60
00:02:31.558 --> 00:02:33.948
and is there a lot of ninny-hood in religion?

61
00:02:33.948 --> 00:02:35.089
There's no question about it.

62
00:02:35.089 --> 00:02:38.118
Tomfoolery, idiotic thinking, superstition,

63
00:02:38.118 --> 00:02:39.782
there's no doubt about it,

64
00:02:39.782 --> 00:02:42.768
but to think that somehow science has discredited

65
00:02:42.768 --> 00:02:44.699
everything that comes under the guise of religion,

66
00:02:44.699 --> 00:02:46.811
including something that I've devoted

67
00:02:46.811 --> 00:02:48.229
a great deal of time to exploring,

68
00:02:48.229 --> 00:02:50.267
and that is the empirical elements,

69
00:02:50.267 --> 00:02:53.050
the profound experiential elements of religion.

70
00:02:53.050 --> 00:02:55.098
Namely, contemplative inquiry.

71
00:02:55.098 --> 00:02:58.031
To somehow discount that as if that just...

72
00:02:58.031 --> 00:03:00.869
Whatever experiences arise from very deep,

73
00:03:00.869 --> 00:03:03.738
sometimes years on end, training

74
00:03:03.738 --> 00:03:06.170
to explore the nature of the mind, consciousness,

75
00:03:06.170 --> 00:03:07.599
its origins and so forth,

76
00:03:07.599 --> 00:03:08.772
and to discount that,

77
00:03:08.772 --> 00:03:10.479
after all they're not scientists,

78
00:03:10.479 --> 00:03:12.409
strikes me as about as open minded as any

79
00:03:12.409 --> 00:03:14.670
religious fundamentalist I've ever met.

80
00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:17.614
What I would call it is a kind of a methodolatry.

81
00:03:17.614 --> 00:03:19.523
That the scientific community, especially those working

82
00:03:19.523 --> 00:03:21.347
in the neurosciences, cognitive sciences,

83
00:03:21.347 --> 00:03:25.720
they're methodologies are, frankly, entirely materialistic.

84
00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:28.195
They're trying to understand the mind

85
00:03:28.195 --> 00:03:31.117
exclusively by way of studying it indirectly,

86
00:03:31.117 --> 00:03:32.888
interrogating people, which is physical,

87
00:03:32.888 --> 00:03:34.722
you can record it.

88
00:03:34.722 --> 00:03:35.736
That's a physical act.

89
00:03:35.736 --> 00:03:37.176
<v Interviewer>Galvanic skin responses, all of it.</v>

90
00:03:37.176 --> 00:03:39.266
<v ->Galvanic skin response, EEG, studying behaviour,</v>

91
00:03:39.266 --> 00:03:41.696
studying fMRI and so forth.

92
00:03:41.696 --> 00:03:43.499
All of these are perfectly viable measures,

93
00:03:43.499 --> 00:03:45.046
and they're all materialistic,

94
00:03:45.046 --> 00:03:47.809
but when your methodology is 100% materialistic,

95
00:03:47.809 --> 00:03:50.229
it should go without saying that, of course,

96
00:03:50.229 --> 00:03:52.181
any conclusions you draw about the mind

97
00:03:52.181 --> 00:03:53.621
will be materialistic.

98
00:03:53.621 --> 00:03:55.199
Which is fair enough if that's

99
00:03:55.199 --> 00:03:56.607
what you're interested in doing,

100
00:03:56.607 --> 00:03:58.762
is adopting materialistic methodologies,

101
00:03:58.762 --> 00:04:02.047
knowing full well that you have no alternative

102
00:04:02.047 --> 00:04:04.713
but to draw materialistic conclusions.

103
00:04:04.713 --> 00:04:06.377
If that's what you'e interested in, why not?

104
00:04:06.377 --> 00:04:08.287
It's a free country, and I'm happy for such people,

105
00:04:08.287 --> 00:04:10.356
but then to turn around and say,

106
00:04:10.356 --> 00:04:12.062
"You see, all the evidence points

107
00:04:12.062 --> 00:04:13.875
"to the mind being material,"

108
00:04:13.875 --> 00:04:15.561
or a function of matter, I say,

109
00:04:15.561 --> 00:04:18.302
"Wait a minute, all the material you've garnered,

110
00:04:18.302 --> 00:04:20.115
"because all of your methodologies..."

111
00:04:20.115 --> 00:04:22.046
This is like a Christian trying to find

112
00:04:22.046 --> 00:04:23.827
evidence for God in the Bible.

113
00:04:23.827 --> 00:04:26.024
And then saying, "You see,

114
00:04:26.024 --> 00:04:28.447
"there's no evidence for atheism in the Bible."

115
00:04:28.447 --> 00:04:31.005
Well, if that's your only book,

116
00:04:31.005 --> 00:04:33.501
and that's the only source of authority,

117
00:04:33.501 --> 00:04:35.656
then one can say, "Duh."

118
00:04:35.656 --> 00:04:37.810
Likewise now, we have these modern scientists,

119
00:04:37.810 --> 00:04:40.509
neurobiologists especially,

120
00:04:40.509 --> 00:04:44.594
their only book is the book of physical nature.

121
00:04:44.594 --> 00:04:46.055
It's the only one they ever study,

122
00:04:46.055 --> 00:04:48.391
it's the only book they have any means of reading,

123
00:04:48.391 --> 00:04:50.386
because all of their technologies, all their methodologies

124
00:04:50.386 --> 00:04:52.967
are good for that and good for nothing else.

125
00:04:52.967 --> 00:04:56.017
But then one can say there isn't anything else.

126
00:04:56.017 --> 00:04:58.673
And I would say, "Yes, there is."

127
00:04:58.673 --> 00:05:02.043
Just as there is a way of studying the stars and planets,

128
00:05:02.043 --> 00:05:06.299
apart from studying old books on astrology and so forth.

129
00:05:06.299 --> 00:05:09.744
The way to understand the nature of the origins and so forth

130
00:05:09.744 --> 00:05:13.445
of stars, planets, galaxies, sun and moon, planet Earth,

131
00:05:13.445 --> 00:05:17.755
is, low and behold, observe very closely.

132
00:05:17.755 --> 00:05:19.109
<v Interviewer>Observation, absolutely.</v>

133
00:05:19.109 --> 00:05:21.125
<v ->Observe the phenomena you're trying to understand.</v>

134
00:05:21.125 --> 00:05:23.279
And here we have the mind, states of consciousness,

135
00:05:23.279 --> 00:05:24.517
mental phenomena,

136
00:05:24.517 --> 00:05:26.384
arising from moment to moment to moment.

137
00:05:26.384 --> 00:05:28.719
Using all the instruments of technology,

138
00:05:28.719 --> 00:05:30.874
you can never observe a single mental event.

139
00:05:30.874 --> 00:05:32.623
Not one.

140
00:05:32.623 --> 00:05:34.937
Not even if you had pain in your knee right now.

141
00:05:34.937 --> 00:05:36.441
I mean, that's a pretty primitive kind of thing.

142
00:05:36.441 --> 00:05:37.646
My knee hurts.

143
00:05:37.646 --> 00:05:39.576
Is there any instrument of technology

144
00:05:39.576 --> 00:05:41.945
that can tell us definitively are you lying,

145
00:05:41.945 --> 00:05:43.577
are you telling the truth?

146
00:05:43.577 --> 00:05:45.123
There is no such instrument.

147
00:05:45.123 --> 00:05:48.447
You can find brain events

148
00:05:48.447 --> 00:05:50.970
that are more or less correlated with pain,

149
00:05:50.970 --> 00:05:52.655
but can we say definitively,

150
00:05:52.655 --> 00:05:54.629
from an objective, scientific perspective,

151
00:05:54.629 --> 00:05:56.516
you're lying or you're telling the truth

152
00:05:56.516 --> 00:05:58.084
when you say you have pain in your knee?

153
00:05:58.084 --> 00:05:59.908
And the answer is we don't know.

154
00:05:59.908 --> 00:06:02.148
And so all of these objectively experienced mental events

155
00:06:02.148 --> 00:06:04.505
are invisible to all the means of technology.

156
00:06:04.505 --> 00:06:06.030
<v Interviewer>And yet our entire life experience</v>

157
00:06:06.030 --> 00:06:09.220
is comprised of nothing but these beliefs and perceptions.

158
00:06:09.220 --> 00:06:11.086
<v ->Precisely, precisely.</v>

159
00:06:11.086 --> 00:06:13.358
And, moreover, it is is possible,

160
00:06:13.358 --> 00:06:15.193
and the great contemplative traditions of the world

161
00:06:15.193 --> 00:06:16.920
have been doing this for millennia,

162
00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:20.110
it is possible not only to take a casual glance,

163
00:06:20.110 --> 00:06:22.424
introspectively, and observe one's thoughts and so forth,

164
00:06:22.424 --> 00:06:24.515
rather like folk astronomy,

165
00:06:24.515 --> 00:06:26.850
leaving us at the level of folk psychology,

166
00:06:26.850 --> 00:06:29.069
but it's also, with rigorous training

167
00:06:29.069 --> 00:06:31.608
that sometimes takes years to master,

168
00:06:31.608 --> 00:06:34.733
it is possible to develop a telescope of the mind.

169
00:06:34.733 --> 00:06:36.993
That is, develop very refined attention

170
00:06:36.993 --> 00:06:38.530
that is stable, that is clear,

171
00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:40.908
enhance your metacognitive abilities,

172
00:06:40.908 --> 00:06:43.201
your ability to monitor your own states of consciousness,

173
00:06:43.201 --> 00:06:46.636
and being probing into the deep space of the mind.

174
00:06:46.636 --> 00:06:49.398
Now, this is a truly scientific approach

175
00:06:49.398 --> 00:06:50.646
to the study of the mind,

176
00:06:50.646 --> 00:06:52.246
in the same way that Galileo's approach

177
00:06:52.246 --> 00:06:54.059
to studying the stars and planets and so forth

178
00:06:54.059 --> 00:06:56.715
was truly scientific, it was empirical.

179
00:06:56.715 --> 00:06:58.827
This is a truly empirical and

180
00:06:58.827 --> 00:07:03.275
it is an avenue of inquiry that's completely been neglected,

181
00:07:03.275 --> 00:07:05.227
and I mean 100% neglected,

182
00:07:05.227 --> 00:07:08.320
by all major institutions of the academy,

183
00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:10.730
of scientific institutions and so forth,

184
00:07:10.730 --> 00:07:13.514
of honing the ability to observe the mind.

185
00:07:13.514 --> 00:07:15.349
So I'm gonna come back to your earlier question.

186
00:07:15.349 --> 00:07:17.321
What got me into this,

187
00:07:17.321 --> 00:07:19.669
the initial question, you might recall,

188
00:07:19.669 --> 00:07:22.580
is that I felt there was really something

189
00:07:22.580 --> 00:07:24.106
to the mind and consciousness,

190
00:07:24.106 --> 00:07:26.281
but I also felt that nothing in my background,

191
00:07:26.281 --> 00:07:28.744
I'd studied biology, various branches of science

192
00:07:28.744 --> 00:07:31.229
and so forth, I thought nothing was getting to it.

193
00:07:31.229 --> 00:07:33.607
Back then, in 1970, they were studying rats and pigeons.

194
00:07:33.607 --> 00:07:35.251
It was primarily behavioural,

195
00:07:35.251 --> 00:07:36.797
and really, let's get real,

196
00:07:36.797 --> 00:07:39.389
how much would I ever learn about your emotional life,

197
00:07:39.389 --> 00:07:40.839
if I'm interested in your mind--

198
00:07:40.839 --> 00:07:42.258
<v Interviewer>Through my pet rat?</v>

199
00:07:42.258 --> 00:07:44.434
<v ->Look at your rat, and give it some crumbs,</v>

200
00:07:44.434 --> 00:07:45.511
and see how many times it will

201
00:07:45.511 --> 00:07:46.684
run through a hoop or something.

202
00:07:46.684 --> 00:07:49.372
I mean, it's really rather bizarre, right?

203
00:07:49.372 --> 00:07:52.177
So I felt here's an area,

204
00:07:52.177 --> 00:07:54.567
the nature of the human, if we use a theological term,

205
00:07:54.567 --> 00:07:56.220
the human soul, the human spirit,

206
00:07:56.220 --> 00:07:58.673
human identity, human mind, consciousness.

207
00:07:58.673 --> 00:07:59.910
What is it?

208
00:07:59.910 --> 00:08:01.766
We are somehow conscious.

209
00:08:01.766 --> 00:08:03.675
Isn't this a wondrous event?

210
00:08:03.675 --> 00:08:05.275
And what is the nature of this?

211
00:08:05.275 --> 00:08:09.403
So I wasn't finding it in your mainstream religion.

212
00:08:09.403 --> 00:08:11.334
We know what that's about,

213
00:08:11.334 --> 00:08:13.488
and the contemplative practice basically isn't there.

214
00:08:13.488 --> 00:08:16.901
Very, very rare, back then it was almost non-existent.

215
00:08:16.901 --> 00:08:19.440
Nowhere in psychology or biology, neuroscience,

216
00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:21.082
nowhere to be found.

217
00:08:21.082 --> 00:08:23.418
So I was just basically utterly disenchanted.

218
00:08:23.418 --> 00:08:25.391
I was disenchanted.

219
00:08:25.391 --> 00:08:27.013
<v Interviewer>Is that when you packed your bags for India?</v>

220
00:08:27.013 --> 00:08:27.994
<v ->Precisely.</v>

221
00:08:27.994 --> 00:08:29.348
Well, I packed my bags first if all

222
00:08:29.348 --> 00:08:31.300
just to get out without my parents

223
00:08:31.300 --> 00:08:33.210
going completely ballistic.

224
00:08:33.210 --> 00:08:35.076
I decided, "I'm getting out of here,

225
00:08:35.076 --> 00:08:36.974
"and I'm going to try to do in a legal way,

226
00:08:36.974 --> 00:08:38.457
"or an acceptable way."

227
00:08:38.457 --> 00:08:41.945
So I took my junior year abroad,

228
00:08:41.945 --> 00:08:44.505
that was one of the options at the University of California,

229
00:08:44.505 --> 00:08:46.190
and I went off to Germany.

230
00:08:46.190 --> 00:08:48.771
I was raised partly in Switzerland, I was fluent in German.

231
00:08:48.771 --> 00:08:51.310
I said, "That'll get me out of here, anyway."

232
00:08:52.980 --> 00:08:54.430
But I was really a seeker.

233
00:08:54.430 --> 00:08:56.414
I mean, I was kind of really classic for my era.

234
00:08:56.414 --> 00:08:59.604
This was 1970, and I was just seeking.

235
00:08:59.604 --> 00:09:02.003
I had existential questions, spiritual questions,

236
00:09:02.003 --> 00:09:04.681
but I wasn't willing to discard either

237
00:09:04.681 --> 00:09:06.920
religion or science.

238
00:09:06.920 --> 00:09:09.374
I just felt there's too much depth, too much insight,

239
00:09:09.374 --> 00:09:10.642
in both of these areas.

240
00:09:10.642 --> 00:09:12.712
While there's an enormous amount of dogmatism

241
00:09:12.712 --> 00:09:14.152
in modern science...

242
00:09:14.152 --> 00:09:17.244
I mean, there's absolutely uncritical, unquestioning

243
00:09:17.244 --> 00:09:22.211
absolute non-skeptical embrace of materialism.

244
00:09:22.211 --> 00:09:24.813
Everything has to be boiled down to matter,

245
00:09:24.813 --> 00:09:26.498
which I find, frankly, laughable.

246
00:09:26.498 --> 00:09:27.906
I mean, matter is a human construct.

247
00:09:27.906 --> 00:09:31.158
We didn't discover it, we defined it, you know?

248
00:09:31.158 --> 00:09:33.004
So for us to define a category,

249
00:09:33.004 --> 00:09:34.850
and, frankly, we are the only ones that defined it.

250
00:09:34.850 --> 00:09:36.087
Not nature.

251
00:09:36.087 --> 00:09:37.782
If nature defined it, we would have simply discovered it

252
00:09:37.782 --> 00:09:39.201
a long time and stuck with it.

253
00:09:39.201 --> 00:09:41.292
But the very category of matter has shifted over the last

254
00:09:41.292 --> 00:09:44.566
at least 400 years, since Copernicus.

255
00:09:44.566 --> 00:09:46.944
So here we've created our own category,

256
00:09:46.944 --> 00:09:48.747
which is a human construct,

257
00:09:48.747 --> 00:09:50.944
and now say the entire universe,

258
00:09:50.944 --> 00:09:55.211
13.7 billion years, with maybe 50 to 100 billion galaxies,

259
00:09:55.211 --> 00:09:57.621
all fits into a construct that we here on planet Earth

260
00:09:57.621 --> 00:10:00.309
have devised over the last century or so.

261
00:10:00.309 --> 00:10:02.912
I think give me a break, you know?

